<TITLE> Stocks end down on profit-taking </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, July 14 (bdnews24.com)Profit-taking led the indices on the twin bourses to close lower on Monday. A price-fall in banks, insurers, mutual funds and some majors in pharmaceuticals pulled the indices on the Dhaka Stock Exchange down from the previous day. The benchmark DGEN or general index maintained a downward curve across the day, to close at 23.85 points or 0.79 percent lower at 2969.35. The DSI or all-share price index lost 21.95 points or 0.85 percent, ending on 2555.49, while the blue-chip DSE-20 finished at 2635.90, slipping 3.08 points or 0.79 percent. Meanwhile, the Chittagong Stock Exchange finished lower due to losses in paper, mutual fund, ICT shares and a slump in the blue chips. The CSCX or selective categories index declined 68.32 points or 1.15 percent to end on 5851.48. The CASPI or all-share price index closed at 9079.35, down by 95.34 points or 1.03 percent. The CSE-30 blue-chip fell 103.49 points or 1.26 percent to end on 8092.74. Brokerage house officials said investors were engaged in a massive sell-off on Monday in a bid to make profits. "Investors sold off bank, insurer, mutual funds and pharmaceuticals majors," an official of brokerage house IDLC Securities told bdnews24.com. Total turnover on the DSE amounted to Tk 2.71 billion from the trading of 18,131,999 shares, down from Sunday's Tk 3.13 billion. Losers outnumbered gainers 150 to 76, while eight issues held steady. Turnover on the port city bourse fell to Tk 390.97 million, from the trading of 4,806,933 shares, down from Tk 409.78 million the previous day. Of the traded 145 issues, 106 lost, 37 gained, and two remained unchanged. Meanwhile, market watchers termed trading rational saying a price correction was about to happen after days of price hike. "The day's trading was quite rational," Bashir Ahmed of brokerage firm Stocks & Bonds told bdnews24.com. Usually a huge sell-of happens after a couple of days of high prices, he added. DSE chief executive Salahuddin Ahmed echoed him and brushed off any possibilities of fear of interventions as the prime reason behind the huge sell-off. "Some investors might have acted out of panic, but a price correction was imminent," added the prime bourse's top official. DSE turnover leader Beximco Pharma continued to lose; falling 3.72 percent to close at Tk 100.80. Square Pharmaceuticals eroded Sunday's gains to end on Tk 5359.25, down by 1.20 percent. ACI followed it to end 9.50 percent higher on Tk 497.60. Beximco lost 2.46 percent to Tk 454.40. Keya Cosmetics s lost after gaining Sunday. It declined 0.92 percent to close at Tk 86.10. Among the other scrips on the turnover boardApex Adelchi Footwear, BATBC, Lanka Bangla Finance and BOC Bangladeshadvanced. AB Bank lost after investors locked in profits. bdn
